Yeah, they hit 5GHz without issues and are stable.
Anyways, like with any leak, it should be taken with a pinch of salt.  But when it comes to hardware, generally the closer to a reveal / launch at an conference, the more accurate it is.
Its going to be what, five more years until I even need to think about a CPU upgrade?
I just want a processor that can last 5 - 10 years before I even need to CONSIDER an upgrade.
And Zen 2 seems to be the perfect time to do it, since this will be a major performance upgrade for the product line.
After this, it should be more akin to Intel's old upgrade cycle.  I'm curious as to how many cores consumer processors will offer in 5 years from now :)
Tbf most new or new-ish CPUs abouts now will last for quite a while.
Indeed.  Single thread seems to be slowing to a crawl until we revolutionize production.
The only way to feasibly go is multi-core, and who knows how long that will take.
Noodle at high-end gaming I reckon 6/8 cores in 5 years.
To that I say, let's see what Zen 2 looks like.  It's extremely likely at this point that AMD will be offering 12 / 16 core processors for AM4.
The price will play a major role in how fast higher core counts are adopted.  On top of performance, but leaks suggest greater than or equal to Intel offerings per thread :)
But I do agree, 8 cores in 5 years seems reasonable.
AMD's stuff is going up in core counts so I'd imagine if games start to properly utilise that, Intel will follow.
I doubt lower-end Intel CPUs will have 8 cores in 5 years though
Long ago, Intel and AMD made bets on how software would go.  Intel went single-core performance, AMD went multi-core.
Intel won that bet, at first.  But it looks like AMD is getting the last laugh.
I still get a laugh thinking back to Intel saying we'd have 10Ghz processors in the 2010-2020 decade.
Are Intel planning on selling radiators?
Hope you don't wanna play Arma 5 in the Summer because you'll make your room hot as Baghdad XD
Intel would be wise to follow AMD's footsteps.  Afaik, Intel designs a single solid die for every processor.  From 2 cores to 18.  AMD has the modular design.
The modular design alows for higher yields.
Also, I predict the future of processing will be multiple dies in everything.  You can only shrink in size so much.
Remember cell phones?  And how they kept making them smaller and smaller?  And then we got smart phones and the trend reversed.
Am I guessing right when I say there was a new Zen 2 leak?
Btw next big thing will probably be die stacking. At least Intel's working hard on that
